[center][b][size=4]This is a 1.0 candidate in active testing — if you play it, PLEASE send feedback or bug reports, and include the MEO.log from that session[/size][/b]
[i](Documents\My Games\Skyrim Special Edition\SKSE\MEO.log)[/i][/center]
[line]

A load-order mod that turns enchanting into socketable, leveling gems. Instead of one baked enchantment, gear carries [i]sockets[/i]: you slot gems that grow with use, swap them between pieces, and combine them. The load order's own enchantments become the gem catalog, so whatever list you play, the gems are balanced to it — nothing is hardcoded.

Built entirely on Linux with no Creation Kit and no xEdit: the plugin is generated byte-by-byte from Python, the install-time patcher is a Mutagen/.NET tool, and the SKSE plugin builds on GitHub Actions.

[size=5][b]Features[/b][/size]

[b]Socketable, leveling gems[/b] — slot a gem into a weapon or armor piece and it grants that effect. Gems earn XP from kills and from souls fed at an enchanting station, climbing levels I–V (magnitude rising each rank); a mastered gem births a fresh copy of itself. Pop a gem back out anytime — it keeps its level and XP. One-click swap moves a gem straight into a filled socket, the old one returning to your pouch.

[b]The world's loot becomes gems[/b] — pre-enchanted gear you find is converted in place into a plain base item plus the matching gem, so the world's enchantments flow into the system instead of competing with it. Artifacts and unique enchantments are left untouched.

[b]Per-load-order calibration[/b] — a run-once installer reads your actual load order and derives every gem's magnitude curve, elemental recipe, and rank ladder from the enchantments that list actually ships. The result suits whatever you play, from vanilla to Requiem-based overhauls.

[b]An enchanting perk tree rebuilt for gems[/b] — the load order's enchanting tree is rewritten in place: a Gem Attunement ladder (potency per rank), Gem Cutter and Soul Feeder, three elemental affinities as parallel choices, Facet Insight for skill/attribute gems, and two perks that add a second, linked socket. Socketed gear can be improved at the grindstone without the Arcane Blacksmith perk (toggle).

[b]Support gems[/b] — Focus, Conduit, and Echo do nothing alone, but linked to a normal gem in a dual-socket item they transform it: Focus sharpens an elemental gem's magnitude, Conduit adapts an off-domain gem to fit the item, and Echo gives a weapon's on-hit effect an area or shares an armor gem's effect with your followers. They level I–III and are rare — found on high-level bosses or hand-placed at a few famous locations.

[b]The Gem Pouch[/b] — a native socketing menu (four skins, full controller support) with a hidden pouch that holds your loose gems so they never clutter your inventory. Gems have no gold value — they're earned, not bought or sold.

[b]Honest limits[/b] — no more than two of the same effect count across your worn gear, so breadth is rewarded over stacking one stat to the ceiling. Feeding, leveling, and conversion are all tunable in the MCM.

[size=5][b]Requirements[/b][/size]

[list]
[*]SKSE64[/*]
[*]Address Library for SKSE Plugins[/*]
[*]SkyUI[/*]
[*]MCM Helper[/*]
[/list]
Developed and tested on Skyrim SE 1.6.1170 against a Requiem-based list (LoreRim) and a pure-vanilla Steam Deck install. The bundled MEO.dll is part of the mod and required.

[size=5][b]Install[/b][/size]

Install the package with your mod manager near the end of the load order, then run [b]MEO.Installer.exe[/b] once from the mod's folder — it adapts MEO to YOUR load order (gem magnitudes and the perk tree). Re-run it after any load-order change. No FOMOD — the options are runtime MCM toggles. Upgrades are save-safe within a major line: the socket data lives in the co-save and migrates itself on load.

[size=5][b]FAQ[/b][/size]

[b]Does this just make me overpowered?[/b]
Power is earned and capped. Gems start weak and level through real use; magnitudes are calibrated to your load order's own strongest enchantments, and no single effect stacks past two copies. It replaces where your enchantments come from, not how strong the list lets them be.

[b]Will it work on my modlist?[/b]
That's the point of the installer — it derives the gems and the tree from your actual load order rather than shipping fixed numbers, so it fits vanilla and heavy overhauls alike. Anything it can't express losslessly it leaves as a normal enchanted item.

[b]Can I turn parts off or tune it?[/b]
Yes. Drop rates, XP rates, gem power, and the temper-without-perk grant are all MCM sliders and toggles.

[b]What happens to my existing enchanted gear?[/b]
Generic enchanted loot converts to a base item plus its gem as you encounter it; artifacts and uniques stay exactly as they are.

[size=5][b]Roadmap[/b][/size]

1.0 is the full system: leveling gems, conversion, the rebuilt perk tree, and the support-gem pillar. Current directions:

[b]More gem families[/b] — let the installer mint gems for enchantment families beyond the current catalog when a list carries them.

[b]More support behaviors[/b] — additional linked-gem support types (Reprisal, Siphon, Final Stand) once the current three are field-proven.

[b]Broader hand-placed acquisition[/b] — more curated locations for the rare support gems.
